<div id="ref-tips" class="ref-panel">
<div class="rsect"><div class="rtitle">Proven strategies from r/pmp and PMP holders</div>
  <div style="display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:10px">
    <div class="motive-tip"><div class="motive-tip-head"><span class="motive-tip-icon">🧠</span><span class="motive-tip-label">Think like PMI, not like yourself</span></div><div class="motive-tip-text">The #1 insight from PMP holders: the exam tests what PMI wants you to do, not what you actually do at work. Always ask "what would PMI's ideal PM do?" — proactive, communicative, process-following, and stakeholder-centric. Your field experience can mislead you.</div></div>
    <div class="motive-tip"><div class="motive-tip-head"><span class="motive-tip-icon">📊</span><span class="motive-tip-label">Score at 75% before booking</span></div><div class="motive-tip-text">Community consensus: do NOT book your exam until you are scoring 75%+ consistently across multiple full simulators (PrepCast, PMI official). One good day is not enough — three consecutive 75%+ sessions is the real green light.</div></div>
    <div class="motive-tip"><div class="motive-tip-head"><span class="motive-tip-icon">⚡</span><span class="motive-tip-label">Active recall beats re-reading</span></div><div class="motive-tip-text">Don't reread PMBOK passively. Instead: do a question, get it wrong, look it up, write a note, revisit the topic. Active recall with spaced repetition (Anki-style) is 2–3x more effective than reading. Use this app's notes tab for this.</div></div>
    <div class="motive-tip"><div class="motive-tip-head"><span class="motive-tip-icon">🎯</span><span class="motive-tip-label">Agile mindset is the differentiator</span></div><div class="motive-tip-text">~50% of questions test agile/hybrid thinking. Most candidates over-prepare the predictive side (they know PMBOK) and under-prepare agile. Spend proportional time: 2 weeks on agile practice guide + Ramdayal's agile videos before your exam month.</div></div>
    <div class="motive-tip"><div class="motive-tip-head"><span class="motive-tip-icon">📅</span><span class="motive-tip-label">Your schedule (10h/week) is realistic</span></div><div class="motive-tip-text">With 10h/week and focused study, most candidates with engineering/PM backgrounds need 10–14 weeks. You have Mon/Wed evenings (2h each) and Sat/Sun (3h each). That's disciplined — follow the pomodoro blocks and log every session to track momentum.</div></div>
    <div class="motive-tip"><div class="motive-tip-head"><span class="motive-tip-icon">📝</span><span class="motive-tip-label">The exam logistics</span></div><div class="motive-tip-text">180 questions · 230 minutes · two optional 10-min breaks. Question types: multiple choice, multiple responses, matching, hotspot, fill-in. Pace: ~1.3 min/question. Don't spend more than 2 min on any single question — flag and return. Budget time for breaks.</div></div>
    <div class="motive-tip"><div class="motive-tip-head"><span class="motive-tip-icon">🏅</span><span class="motive-tip-label">Application requirements</span></div><div class="motive-tip-text">You need 35 contact hours (Udemy courses qualify) + 36 months leading projects (with a 4-year degree) OR 60 months (without). Your systems engineering background at Alstom/Continental/Stellantis almost certainly qualifies. Apply early — audit takes 2–4 weeks.</div></div>
