// ── QUESTIONS ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
const Q=[
{d:'people',s:'conflict',q:'Two team members have been in conflict for weeks on technical approach, damaging morale. Best first step?',o:['Escalate to sponsor','Force a decision','Facilitate a problem-solving session where both present views and the team reaches consensus','Document as a risk'],a:2,e:'PMI ranks problem-solving (confronting) highest for conflict resolution — it addresses root causes and builds trust. Forcing produces compliance without resolution; escalation is a last resort.'},
{d:'people',s:'motivation',q:'Herzberg\'s Two-Factor Theory: which action TRULY motivates a team member who already has good pay and job security?',o:['Salary bonus','Challenging work with more responsibility and recognition','Better physical conditions','Guaranteed job security another year'],a:1,e:'Herzberg separates hygiene factors (salary, security — prevent dissatisfaction but do not motivate) from true motivators (achievement, recognition, growth). Only motivators drive genuine performance improvement.'},
{d:'people',s:'leadership',q:'New team member is highly skilled but lacks confidence in the new environment. Which situational leadership style fits best?',o:['Delegating — full autonomy','Directing — detailed instructions','Coaching — guidance plus active encouragement of their input','Laissez-faire'],a:2,e:'Coaching suits high competence/low commitment (Hersey & Blanchard). The person has the skill but needs confidence. Coaching provides direction while valuing input, unlike pure directing which ignores capability.'},
{d:'people',s:'team',q:'A team establishing norms and working cohesively after initial conflict is in which Tuckman stage?',o:['Forming','Storming','Norming','Performing'],a:2,e:'Norming follows Storming. The team resolved interpersonal conflict and is now establishing working agreements and trust. Performing is peak productivity that follows norming.'},
{d:'people',s:'ethics',q:'Vendor offers sports tickets worth $600. Company policy allows gifts up to $75. What do you do?',o:['Accept — common practice','Accept and donate them','Decline and inform the vendor of your company policy','Report vendor to procurement'],a:2,e:'PMI Code of Ethics: gifts exceeding policy limits create real or perceived conflicts of interest. A polite decline referencing policy is correct — accepting regardless of disposition violates integrity standards.'},
{d:'people',s:'ethics',q:'Sponsor pressures you to cut estimate by 25% for budget approval. You believe the estimate is accurate. Most ethical response?',o:['Reduce it to preserve the relationship','Submit lower estimate and manage the gap','Present original estimate with supporting analysis and explain the risks of underestimating','Submit both and let sponsor choose'],a:2,e:'PMI Code of Ethics requires honesty and accuracy. Knowingly submitting an inaccurate estimate harms the organization. Presenting facts and consequences is the professional obligation.'},
{d:'people',s:'ethics',q:'A team member tells you privately a colleague is falsifying status reports. Your FIRST action?',o:['Report immediately to sponsor','Confront in team meeting','Verify the facts independently first','Ignore it'],a:2,e:'PMI requires verification before reporting. Acting on unverified information could be unfair to the accused. Confirm facts first, then report through appropriate channels.'},
{d:'people',s:'leadership',q:'A PM removes obstacles, seeks team input before deciding, and prioritizes team growth. Which approach?',o:['Autocratic','Transactional','Servant leadership','Laissez-faire'],a:2,e:'Servant leadership is the PMI-preferred and agile-aligned model: the PM serves the team by enabling, coaching, protecting, and empowering rather than directing and controlling.'},
{d:'people',s:'stakeholder',q:'An executive has high power and low interest. Best engagement strategy?',o:['Involve in all decisions','Send detailed weekly reports','Keep satisfied with concise high-level updates; monitor for interest changes','Assign them a team role'],a:2,e:'Power/Interest grid: High Power, Low Interest = "Keep Satisfied." These stakeholders need to feel informed and comfortable but do not want operational detail.'},
{d:'people',s:'negotiation',q:'Sponsor wants 20% budget cut with no scope or deadline change. Not feasible. Best response?',o:['Accept and manage shortfall','Refuse and escalate','Present impact analysis and propose options: reduce scope, extend timeline, or phase delivery','Ask team to find savings secretly'],a:2,e:'PMI expects the PM to present facts and trade-off options. Showing alternatives respects the sponsor\'s authority while providing a realistic picture — the core of principled negotiation.'},
{d:'people',s:'diversity',q:'HQ colleagues dominate virtual meetings; remote members rarely speak up. Best structural fix?',o:['Require all to attend HQ monthly','Run all meetings fully virtual so no one is "in the room"','Send remote members written summaries','Create a separate remote sub-team'],a:1,e:'Leveling the playing field — everyone virtual — removes the social dynamic that silences remote participants. This is the standard distributed team inclusion technique.'},
{d:'people',s:'team',q:'High-performing team member resigns citing lack of growth. Project is in a critical phase. Do FIRST?',o:['Offer salary increase','Honest conversation to understand concerns and explore options','Ask HR to block resignation','Reassign their work'],a:1,e:'Understanding root cause is essential before acting. Non-financial solutions — challenging work, mentoring, recognition — may address the real concern. Acting without understanding typically misses the point.'},
{d:'people',s:'agile',q:'Product owner is frequently unavailable, causing sprint delays. Scrum Master should?',o:['Answer questions on PO\'s behalf','Replace the PO immediately','Coach PO on their accountability and arrange better collaboration windows','Let team decide without PO input'],a:2,e:'The Scrum Master serves the PO by coaching them in Scrum. PO unavailability is an impediment. Coaching — addressing root cause — is correct. Bypassing the PO removes accountability from the right role.'},
{d:'people',s:'agile',q:'Scrum impediment the Scrum Master cannot resolve alone. What should happen?',o:['Remove it from sprint backlog','Extend the sprint','Escalate to someone with authority to remove it','Let the team work around it'],a:2,e:'The Scrum Master escalates impediments beyond their authority to resolve. Leaving the team blocked violates the Scrum Master\'s accountability to protect the team\'s delivery ability.'},
{d:'process',s:'risk',q:'Risk has 30% probability and $90,000 impact. Mitigation costs $20,000. Should you mitigate?',o:['No — too expensive','Yes — EMV analysis supports it','Only if sponsor approves','Transfer instead'],a:1,e:'EMV = 0.30 × $90,000 = $27,000. Since mitigation cost ($20,000) < EMV ($27,000), mitigation is cost-justified. This is the core quantitative risk decision framework.'},
{d:'process',s:'evm',q:'BAC=$400K, EV=$200K, AC=$240K, PV=$220K. What is the CPI?',o:['0.83 — project is over budget','0.91 — project is ahead of schedule','1.10 — project is under budget','0.83 — project will finish on time'],a:0,e:'CPI = EV/AC = $200K/$240K = 0.833. CPI < 1 means cost overrun — for every $1 spent, only $0.83 of value is delivered. SPI = EV/PV = 0.91, also behind schedule.'},
{d:'process',s:'evm',q:'Same project (BAC=$400K, EV=$200K, AC=$240K). EAC assuming future work continues at current CPI?',o:['$400,000','$440,000','$480,000','$360,000'],a:2,e:'EAC = BAC/CPI = $400K / 0.833 ≈ $480,000. The most common EAC formula — assumes cost efficiency experienced so far continues for remaining work.'},
{d:'process',s:'evm',q:'TCPI (based on BAC) is 1.18. What does this mean?',o:['Project is 18% ahead of schedule','Remaining work must be done at 18% higher efficiency than planned — likely unachievable','CPI is 1.18','Project will finish 18% under budget'],a:1,e:'TCPI = (BAC−EV)/(BAC−AC). Value > 1.0 means the team must work more efficiently on remaining work. Values above 1.10 are generally considered unrealistic without scope or schedule changes.'},
{d:'process',s:'evm',q:'PV=$600K, EV=$500K, AC=$560K. What are CV and SV?',o:['CV=−$60K (over budget), SV=−$100K (behind schedule)','CV=$60K (under budget), SV=$100K (ahead)','CV=−$100K, SV=−$60K','CV=$40K, SV=−$100K'],a:0,e:'CV = EV−AC = −$60K (over budget). SV = EV−PV = −$100K (behind schedule). Both negative — simultaneously over budget and behind schedule. Immediate corrective action required.'},
{d:'process',s:'evm',q:'EAC=$850K and BAC=$750K. VAC and what does it mean?',o:['$100K — will finish under budget','−$100K — forecast overrun of $100K','$850K — total project value','0 — on track'],a:1,e:'VAC = BAC−EAC = −$100K. Negative VAC means the project is forecast to overrun the original budget by $100K. Requires corrective action or scope negotiation.'},
{d:'process',s:'schedule',q:'Activity A finishes Day 15. Activity B has FS dependency with 4-day lag. Earliest B can start?',o:['Day 15','Day 16','Day 19','Day 20'],a:2,e:'Finish-to-Start with lag: B can start 4 days after A finishes. Day 15 + 4 lag = Day 19. Lags add waiting time between dependent activities.'},
{d:'process',s:'schedule',q:'Which schedule compression preserves scope and quality but increases coordination risk?',o:['Crashing','Resource leveling','Fast tracking','Schedule baseline update'],a:2,e:'Fast tracking overlaps activities planned sequentially — no extra cost but increased risk and potential rework. Crashing adds resources (adds cost). Fast tracking trades risk for time without changing scope.'},
{d:'process',s:'schedule',q:'Activity: O=4 days, M=7, P=16. PERT estimate and standard deviation?',o:['PERT=8.0, SD=2','PERT=7.67, SD=2','PERT=8.0, SD=3','PERT=9.0, SD=3'],a:0,e:'PERT = (4+28+16)/6 = 8.0 days. SD = (P−O)/6 = (16−4)/6 = 2.0 days. ±1 SD (6–10 days) gives ~68% confidence range.'},
{d:'process',s:'schedule',q:'Activity A has zero total float. Activity B has 5 days total float. Which is on the critical path?',o:['B only','A only','Both','Neither'],a:1,e:'Zero total float = critical path. Any delay to A directly delays project completion. B has 5 days of slack before impacting the end date.'},
{d:'process',s:'quality',q:'Control chart: 8 consecutive points on one side of the mean, all within control limits. Action needed?',o:['None — points are within limits','Investigate — non-random pattern signals special cause even within limits','Expand the control limits','Replace the operator'],a:1,e:'Rule of Seven/Eight: consecutive points on the same side signal non-random (special cause) variation even within limits. The process is out of statistical control and must be investigated.'},
{d:'process',s:'quality',q:'Cost of non-conformance ($200K) exceeds conformance ($120K). What to recommend?',o:['Reduce quality spending','Invest more in prevention — non-conformance costs exceed prevention cost','Outsource quality','Accept current profile'],a:1,e:'Cost of Quality: when non-conformance (rework, warranty, failure) > conformance (prevention, appraisal), increasing prevention investment is economically justified.'},
{d:'process',s:'scope',q:'Customer calls your team directly requesting a "small" change, bypassing change control. What do you do?',o:['Allow it — minor change','Do it informally, document afterward','All changes must go through integrated change control regardless of size','Ask sponsor to decide'],a:2,e:'All changes, regardless of perceived size, must go through integrated change control. "Minor" changes often have unforeseen cost, schedule, or quality impacts. Bypassing the process is scope creep by definition.'},
{d:'process',s:'scope',q:'The 100% rule in WBS means:',o:['Work packages each take 100 hours','All nodes must have 100% resource allocation','WBS captures 100% of project scope — nothing more, nothing less','WBS must have exactly 100 work packages'],a:2,e:'The 100% rule: the WBS captures ALL deliverables and work required — no more, no less. Work outside the WBS is unauthorized; all planned work must be represented.'},
{d:'process',s:'procurement',q:'Cost-Plus-Fixed-Fee (CPFF) contract. Vendor\'s material costs increase significantly. What happens to the fee?',o:['Fee increases proportionally','Fee stays fixed — only actual costs change','Contract auto-renegotiates','Buyer and vendor share the increase'],a:1,e:'CPFF: the fee is fixed regardless of actual costs. The buyer pays all actual costs plus the fixed fee. Cost risk lies entirely with the buyer — costs can rise, but the fee does not change.'},
{d:'process',s:'risk',q:'Monte Carlo shows 65% probability of completing by Day 200. Contractual deadline is Day 185. What to do?',o:['Project will definitely miss — escalate immediately','Significant probability of missing Day 185 — schedule risk response needed','Fine — 65% is passing','Reduce scope immediately'],a:1,e:'Monte Carlo quantifies uncertainty. 65% confidence at Day 200 means much less probability of hitting Day 185. This triggers risk response: schedule compression, scope review, or expectation management.'},
{d:'process',s:'risk',q:'Risk register: A=40%/$50K, B=25%/$80K, C=60%/$30K. Which has highest EMV?',o:['C ($18K)','B ($20K)','A ($20K)','A and B tied at $20K'],a:3,e:'EMV: A = 0.40×$50K = $20K. B = 0.25×$80K = $20K. C = 0.60×$30K = $18K. A and B are tied at $20K — both should be prioritized for response planning.'},
{d:'process',s:'change',q:'Change approved by CCB. PM\'s NEXT action?',o:['Implement immediately','Communicate the decision and update all affected plan components and baselines','Archive the change request','Ask team to re-estimate'],a:1,e:'After CCB approval: communicate, update all affected documents and baselines, THEN implement. Skipping baseline updates creates misaligned records and undermines future performance measurement.'},
{d:'process',s:'integration',q:'Taking over a project mid-execution. Review FIRST?',o:['Budget spreadsheet','Project charter','Team performance reviews','Latest customer emails'],a:1,e:'The project charter is foundational — authorizes the project, names the PM, and states high-level scope and constraints. It is the starting point for understanding any project.'},
{d:'process',s:'close',q:'All deliverables accepted. Most important activity before formal closure?',o:['Archive all documents','Release team members','Capture lessons learned and update organizational process assets','Transfer operational responsibility'],a:2,e:'Lessons learned are the mechanism for organizational improvement. They feed into OPAs and must be documented before archiving and team release — a strategic, not administrative, obligation.'},
{d:'process',s:'agile',q:'PO wants a major feature added after sprint planning. Team is mid-sprint at full capacity. Correct response?',o:['Add it — PO decides sprint content','Reject it permanently','Add to product backlog; PO prioritizes for a future sprint','Stop sprint and re-plan'],a:2,e:'The sprint backlog is protected once the sprint starts. New scope goes to the product backlog where the PO prioritizes it. This protects the team\'s sprint commitment while keeping the backlog current.'},
{d:'process',s:'agile',q:'Agile team velocity has been 45 story points/sprint for 5 sprints. 225 story points remain. Forecast?',o:['4 sprints','5 sprints','6 sprints','Cannot be determined'],a:1,e:'225 ÷ 45 = 5 sprints. Velocity-based forecasting uses historical throughput to project remaining work, assuming stable team and consistent story sizing.'},
{d:'process',s:'agile',q:'Kanban board: work piling in "Code Review" for 2 weeks. First action?',o:['Add more developers','Increase WIP limit for Code Review','Investigate and address the bottleneck constraint','Switch to Scrum'],a:2,e:'A visible bottleneck means that stage has insufficient capacity or a systemic issue. Increasing WIP limits worsens the pile-up. Addressing the constraint (more reviewers, clearer criteria, automation) is the lean/Kanban approach.'},
{d:'process',s:'hybrid',q:'Software project uses sprints for development but requires regulatory sign-off at milestones. Best describes:',o:['Pure Scrum','Pure waterfall','Hybrid lifecycle — agile delivery with predictive governance gates','Iterative without milestones'],a:2,e:'Regulated industries use hybrid approaches: agile delivery within phases combined with formal stage-gate approvals required by compliance. This is the most common real-world lifecycle.'},
{d:'process',s:'agile',q:'Retrospective: team members hesitate to raise issues for fear of judgment. Root cause?',o:['Team lacks agile experience','Wrong retrospective format','Psychological safety is absent — members fear reprisal','Scrum Master not facilitating'],a:2,e:'Psychological safety — the belief one can speak up without punishment — is the foundational condition for effective retrospectives. Its absence is the most common reason retrospectives fail to surface real issues.'},
{d:'process',s:'wbs',q:'After completing the WBS, next step before scheduling?',o:['Assign resources to work packages','Develop WBS dictionary','Begin work on first deliverable','Submit to sponsor'],a:1,e:'The WBS dictionary defines each work package: scope, deliverables, acceptance criteria, responsible party. Essential context before scheduling — without it the schedule lacks definition.'},
{d:'process',s:'communication',q:'Executive says "I feel like I\'m always the last to know about problems." Best PM response?',o:['Apologize and send more emails','Conduct communications review, identify gap, update communication plan','Tell them it was in the status reports','Add them to all project emails'],a:1,e:'This signals a communications management failure. Root cause may be wrong format, frequency, channel, or detail level. Systematic review and plan revision — not volume increase — is the correct response.'},
{d:'business',s:'benefits',q:'Project NPV drops from $300K to $85K due to market changes after 18 months. What should the PM do?',o:['Continue — too far along to stop','Update business case, present revised financials, recommend go/no-go decision','Reduce costs to compensate','Ask team to increase scope'],a:1,e:'Projects exist to deliver business value. When the business case no longer justifies the investment, the PM must present this to decision-makers. Continuing blindly ignores strategic interests.'},
{d:'business',s:'governance',q:'Who is MOST accountable for benefits realization six months after project delivery?',o:['The project manager','The project team','The business owner / sponsor','The PMO director'],a:2,e:'Benefits realization occurs in operations after project closure. The business owner/sponsor is accountable — they own the outcome in the operating environment. The PM delivers the capability; the business owns results.'},
{d:'business',s:'compliance',q:'Mid-project, deliverable found non-compliant with a new regulation enacted during execution. Do FIRST?',o:['Complete as planned and note the gap','Notify sponsor, assess impact, initiate change request','Submit deliverable and let regulator flag it','Apply for exemption before informing sponsor'],a:1,e:'Regulatory compliance is non-negotiable. Immediate notification, impact assessment, and a formal change request are required. Attempting to bypass violates both legal and PMI ethical standards.'},
{d:'business',s:'strategy',q:'PMO asks you to release two team members to a higher-priority project. Best response?',o:['Refuse — deadline cannot be met','Accept without analysis','Analyze impact and present to portfolio decision-makers for informed choice','Negotiate informally'],a:2,e:'Portfolio trade-off decisions belong to portfolio level, not individual PMs. The PM\'s role is to provide accurate, honest impact analysis so decision-makers can make informed choices.'},
{d:'business',s:'org',q:'In a weak matrix, a team member frequently prioritizes functional work over your project. Structural reason?',o:['Member lacks professionalism','Your project is not a portfolio priority','Functional managers retain primary authority in weak matrix — PMs have limited formal power','You are not communicating clearly'],a:2,e:'In a weak matrix, functional authority dominates. PMs rely on influence, negotiation, and sponsorship rather than formal authority. This is a structural reality, not a personal failure.'},
{d:'business',s:'value',q:'Total benefits $720K, total costs $300K. BCR and what it indicates?',o:['BCR=0.42 — costs exceed benefits','BCR=2.4 — benefits exceed costs; project is financially viable','BCR=420,000 — net benefit only','BCR=1.0 — break even'],a:1,e:'BCR = Benefits/Costs = $720K/$300K = 2.4. BCR > 1 means benefits exceed costs. A BCR of 2.4 means each $1 invested returns $2.40.'},
{d:'business',s:'lifecycle',q:'Product meets all documented requirements but customer says it "doesn\'t feel right." Root cause?',o:['Poor execution','Requirements elicitation was inadequate — actual needs were not fully captured','Scope creep occurred','Customer changed their mind'],a:1,e:'When a product meets requirements but fails to satisfy, requirements were incomplete or incorrect. This is an elicitation failure — the gap between stated and actual needs.'},
{d:'business',s:'change',q:'Significant employee resistance emerged during an ERP rollout. Most effective change management approach?',o:['Mandate adoption through policy','Involve key resistors in solution design and create change champions','Accelerate rollout to shorten resistance','Replace resistant employees'],a:1,e:'Involving resistors in solution design converts critics into advocates, addressing the root cause (lack of voice and ownership). Supported by Kotter\'s 8-step model and Prosci ADKAR.'},
{d:'people',s:'agile',q:'Management demands a fixed 12-month plan before the agile project starts. Best approach?',o:['Refuse and educate on agile','Produce full waterfall plan and abandon agile','Provide high-level roadmap with release milestones and cost ranges while educating on rolling wave planning','Ignore request'],a:2,e:'Skilled PMs bridge agile and organizational governance needs. A roadmap with milestones and budget ranges satisfies management\'s predictability needs while preserving adaptive planning at sprint level.'},
{d:'process',s:'agile',q:'Product backlog item not estimated or refined. PO wants it in next sprint. What must happen first?',o:['PO can override — straight to sprint','Must be estimated and refined before sprint planning','Team votes on inclusion','Scrum Master decides'],a:1,e:'Backlog refinement is a prerequisite for sprint planning. Items must be well-defined, estimated, and have clear acceptance criteria before the team can commit to delivering them.'},
{d:'process',s:'agile',q:'Retrospective finds unclear acceptance criteria are the main cause of rework. Best corrective action?',o:['Add more testing phases','PO writes all criteria alone','Implement Definition of Done and involve team in writing criteria during refinement','Hire a business analyst'],a:2,e:'Unclear criteria during refinement is a common rework source. The DoD and team involvement in writing criteria ensures shared understanding before development begins.'},
{d:'people',s:'stakeholder',q:'Powerful stakeholder group not identified during planning. Project is 60% complete. What to do?',o:['Continue — too late','Identify and engage them immediately, assess impact, update stakeholder management plan','Document as lessons learned only','Inform sponsor and wait'],a:1,e:'It is never too late to identify and engage stakeholders. Unengaged powerful stakeholders can derail near-complete projects. Immediate identification, impact assessment, and structured engagement is always correct.'},
{d:'people',s:'stakeholder',q:'A resistant stakeholder starts raising valid technical concerns at steering committee meetings. What to do?',o:['Limit their access','Escalate resistance to sponsor','Engage directly, incorporate valid feedback, leverage their expertise','Document resistance as a project risk'],a:2,e:'Resistant stakeholders raising valid points should be engaged, not suppressed. Converting a critic into a contributor improves the project outcome — the highest-value stakeholder engagement outcome.'},
{d:'process',s:'lessons',q:'Team considers lessons learned a formality. Best argument for doing it thoroughly?',o:['Required by project charter','PMI requires for certification','Lessons learned feed OPAs — they directly improve future project performance and reduce repeated mistakes','Sponsor requested it'],a:2,e:'Lessons learned enable organizational learning — the mechanism by which organizations improve. OPAs built from lessons are a competitive advantage, not a compliance checkbox.'},
{d:'people',s:'influence',q:'No formal authority over a matrix team member who misses project meetings. Most effective approach?',o:['Report to HR','Send written warning','Understand constraints, align with functional manager, make participation more valuable','Remove from team'],a:2,e:'Matrix PMs rely on influence, not authority. Understanding barriers, aligning with the functional manager, and making involvement valuable addresses root causes. Coercive approaches damage relationships.'},
{d:'process',s:'risk',q:'A known risk occurs. Response plan was prepared. First action?',o:['Update risk register','Notify project sponsor','Implement the pre-planned response','Convene emergency risk review'],a:2,e:'When a known risk occurs, you execute the pre-planned response immediately — that is the entire point of proactive risk management. Documentation and communication follow implementation.'},
{d:'process',s:'evm',q:'BAC=$500K, EV=$300K, AC=$320K, PV=$350K. What is the SPI?',o:['0.86 — behind schedule','0.94 — slightly behind','1.17 — ahead of schedule','0.86 — over budget'],a:0,e:'SPI = EV/PV = $300K/$350K = 0.857 ≈ 0.86. SPI < 1 means behind schedule — only $0.86 of planned progress achieved per $1 of schedule.'},
{d:'process',s:'cost',q:'In a fixed-price contract with well-defined scope, cost risk primarily falls on?',o:['The buyer','The vendor — they absorb cost overruns','Neither — risk is equal','The PM'],a:1,e:'Fixed-price contracts transfer cost risk to the vendor. If costs exceed the fixed price, the vendor absorbs the overrun. The buyer has cost certainty. Poor scope definition reverses this advantage.'},
{d:'people',s:'team',q:'Team successfully completes a challenging phase. Most appropriate PM action?',o:['Brief them immediately on next phase','Acknowledge and celebrate the achievement before moving on','Document success in lessons learned only','Send summary email to sponsor'],a:1,e:'Recognition is a proven motivator (Herzberg, Maslow). Acknowledging achievement builds morale, reinforces high performance, and prepares the team for the next challenge.'},
{d:'business',s:'strategy',q:'Project is 70% complete but its strategic objective is now irrelevant due to a market shift. PM should recommend?',o:['Continue — 70% spent','Reduce scope to finish faster','Recommend termination or re-scoping to align with current strategy','Transfer to another team'],a:2,e:'Sunk cost fallacy: resources already spent are irrelevant. The decision is based on future value vs. future cost. If the strategic objective no longer exists, continuing wastes resources.'},
{d:'process',s:'quality',q:'Quality audit: a process has been consistently skipped. No visible defects yet. What to do?',o:['Approve the shortcut — results justify it','Accept for now','Address and document the deviation — skipped processes are systemic risks regardless of current quality','Replace the responsible person'],a:2,e:'Quality management focuses on conformance to process, not just results. A skipped process is a systemic risk — defects may be latent. "No defects yet" is not the same as "no risk."'},
{d:'process',s:'integration',q:'Conflicting status data from different tools. Sponsor needs a report today. What to do?',o:['Send most favorable data','Delay until all data reconciled','Quickly reconcile, identify most reliable source, provide honest report noting the discrepancy','Ask IT to fix the PMIS first'],a:2,e:'Timely, honest reporting is the PM\'s obligation. The sponsor needs accurate data. Reconcile quickly, report transparently, flag discrepancies — do not delay or cherry-pick data.'},
{d:'process',s:'communication',q:'Stakeholder requests detailed technical reports they never read. What to do?',o:['Continue — they requested it','Stop without consulting them','Review actual communication needs and adjust format, frequency, or detail with their agreement','Escalate to their manager'],a:2,e:'Communication management is about effectiveness, not compliance with stated preferences. If reports are unused, format or content may be wrong. A collaborative review prevents wasted effort.'},
{d:'people',s:'coaching',q:'Technically brilliant team member considered for lead role struggles with interpersonal skills. Best developmental approach?',o:['Assign full role and let them learn','Assign to someone else','Provide coaching, a mentor, graduated leadership opportunities, and clear interpersonal expectations','Keep them in technical role permanently'],a:2,e:'Development plans for high-potential members must be structured and supported. Coaching + mentoring + graduated responsibility builds capability safely.'},
{d:'process',s:'hybrid',q:'Hybrid project: sprints for software, predictive for hardware. Hardware delay impacts a planned sprint. Do FIRST?',o:['Stop all sprints until hardware arrives','Resequence sprints to avoid hardware-dependent work and raise dependency as a project risk','Crash hardware procurement','Cancel hardware component'],a:1,e:'Adaptive sequencing is a core hybrid PM skill. Sprint work not dependent on delayed hardware can continue. The dependency should be tracked as a risk to prevent future surprises.'},
{d:'people',s:'ethics',q:'Competitor filed a patent on a technical approach your team is developing. What to do?',o:['Continue — patents hard to enforce','Implement and let legal handle future claims','Immediately involve legal counsel, assess IP risk, identify alternatives or licensing options','Remove feature without notifying stakeholders'],a:2,e:'IP risk requires immediate expert involvement. The PM should not make IP judgments but must escalate promptly so legal and business stakeholders can make informed decisions.'},
